segments.text: This is an interview with Mike Arisco by Stephen Huggs in Houston, Texas, 11-5-88.
I need your name, place of birth, location and date for Vietnam.
Okay, my name is Mike Arisco.
I was, at that time, I was living in Port Opera, graduating from Thomas Jefferson in Port Opera.
I was in the United States Marine Corps in 1966 through 69, but entered Vietnam in 67 through 69.
All right.
And what service organization were you in?
Marine Corps.
In the Marine Corps.
And what was your job specialty?
I was 2533 was what my specialty was, which is communications.
But a lot of times you get stuck in some of the weirdest jobs while you were there.
I was with H&S, 3rd Engineers is what I was working with.
Originally, I started out as sweeping highways in the morning for landmines.
That's what my original job was, beginning at communications.
Later took over communications of the area and then started working.
We did toward the end of my first tour, then through my next tour was patrol, working with H&S.
Were you communication on patrol?
No.
No, I wasn't.
Okay.
When I say no, I wasn't communications.
When I became a sergeant, I was still part of communications, but I enjoyed going out more than sitting in the Cointree area.
I just didn't like sitting there.
I liked taking off.
Now, when you say communications, just about everybody in our squad could work the communications.
We all took turns with it, if that's what you mean.
We had a radio operator.
Okay.
Okay.
All right.
And why in particular did you choose to fight and be not?
Because I was scared to go to jail.
At that time, no one wants to go to jail.
No one wants to die.
But I felt I was scared, as everybody else was.
But I was afraid that if I didn't go, I'm going to jail.
And I was more afraid of that.
I was more afraid of what would happen to me if I didn't go than if I did go.
Hmm.
And why did you choose the Marine Corps?
Because I'm stupid.
No, I picked the Marine Corps because of my personality and the way that I am.
I am a person who likes to do spontaneous things.
When I entered the Marine Corps, I was fooling, of course, with the lower Neanderthal people.
Some of the dumbest things they made us do.
But I could get away with more.

if i if i did not show up for three days to an area let's say when i when i was in uh when i was in the uh san diego let's say when i was stationed there for a while which was near oceanside or wherever i was stationed i'd go meet some girl be gone for three days and just say i lost my way back or i had car trouble and they'll believe me it was it was unique how ignorance

confess your own ignorance and but again i also looked at it when i was in the marine corps we had a tradition we didn't leave anybody behind if someone was shot we didn't leave them we took them back body and all sometimes so uh again that's dumb reasons i guess but that was my reason all right did you receive any uh instruction about the country or the nature of the conflict no that was when i received the information
Okay, let's start over here.
When I entered the Marine Corps, I spent boot camp, and then I went to weapons training.
We went to Camp Pendleton for about six weeks to learn how to use certain weapons.
There we had maybe a few days of talking about Vietnam because that's what everybody was talking about, but nothing on Vietnam.
It wasn't until I really got into country
And that, I think, was our major problem.
I don't know if other units did have any indoctrination of the country.
We didn't.
And I think one of our problems, we never understood the people.
And not understanding them, we insulted them more than we ever, by helping them, we insulted them more.
One example, when you go into a village, when kids run up to you, you always just say, hey, here's some candy.
And you're trying to be nice to them when you know it's a friendly village.

At that point, when we first walked into a village, we did not know that before I even stepped into the village, I've already insulted everyone in that village four and five times and never even knew it because I was never told of their customs.
And I guess you could say it's the Marine Corps' fault because we're out there fighting a war.
But again, we lost the villagers.
We never had them on our side.
Of course, they were more afraid of the enemy.
than they were of us.
But like when you enter a village, the first person you're supposed to talk to is the oldest and the elder of the village.
Where you would stop and say hello to a little kid and you'd give them candy, you've insulted the oldest person in that village.
You've insulted the entire village.
Also, touching the top of a child's head is very, the top of a child's head in our area was very, very sacred.
And it was like a magnet.
They said that if you touched the top of a child's head,
it would suck the kindness out of their body into your body.
And they believed it, and that's part of their beliefs or their customs.
So first thing you do is grab a little kid's head and you shake the, hey, how you doing?
You just, to those people, you've just taken all the kindness from that child, and you now own it.
And you just insulted the family.
Yeah.
What is your very first memory of the country you were on?
The smell.
The country stunk.
I landed in Da Nang, is where I first landed, and I was there in Da Nang about three days, but the first thing that I noticed, no, I wasn't there about three days, about two days I was in Da Nang.
Getting off the plane, when I was on those little steps coming off, the smell, the stench, it smelled like the whole country was a cesspool.
At that time, I did not know why, but then I thought everybody in the country, again, that was my ignorance of not knowing the people.
Vietnam stunk because
It's rice paddies.
It's 90%, at least the areas I was in, it's mostly rice paddy and jungle.
They use natural ingredients to fertilize their rice paddies.
So everything stunk.
The people had different ways of life.
Again, the smell was the worst, I think.
That's the first thing I remember.
I still can smell the, at times, the stench of the country.
Of course, they could have been burning
Yeah, sure.
I thought they could have been burning the shitters at that time, you know, the outhouses.
And if they were, you know, the smell was going across the tarmac, which was our denang at that time.
Did you at any time feel that South Vietnam was
too corrupt or corrupt?
South Vietnam could never win the war.
We kind of knew that.
What we wanted was to spend our tour and get out.
The few men that I met, we had an interpreter, and over a year we became half-decent friends.
He didn't trust me, and of course a lot of times I didn't quite trust him, but we became as best friends as we could.
He had a brother that he paid to get out of war.
There's a lot of people that could pay their way out of the army.
Corruption was real, real big.
So we knew that.
And we just knew there's no way that that...
There had to be a revolution to overthrow the corruption.
So it was just no chance.
And did you ever feel that the Arvin were ineffective or... Again, a problem... We had an Arvin.
Again, one of our interpreters was an Arvin.
And...
He knew when we went out on patrol that, again, they had a different belief.
Now, again, this is the area I was in.

Before we get started, I've got to let you know, over the years I've found that talking to other people about Vietnam, what happens to me in Vietnam, you can talk to 50 other guys, and all 50 have different interpretations, different ideas of Vietnam, even different terrain, everything, which is so different in areas.
So I'm giving you what I saw and what I interpreted from this.
The Arvin that I had in my unit, the first time we fought, you know, we had a small engagement.
He wanted to run.
I mean, he wanted to run the first thing, and he just knew the moment he got up, I would shoot him in the back.
He knew that from the start, that any one of my units was going to kill him the moment that he got up to run.
I thought he was a coward.
I thought he was an absolute coward.
And until one day, he's changed me a lot, my interpretation of Vietnam because he showed me their point of view, which was so different from mine.
One day we were sitting there talking and I said, you know, I can't believe I'm in your country fighting for you and you're nothing but a bunch of cowards always running.
And he got a little upset with me and he said, you are a

a visitor in our country you're here to help us but you're so wrong and he he was very angry he told me he said you you marines up here uh brag about having the ten to one kill ratio in other words uh they'd say that our units up in the north had ten to one ratio would kill ten of the enemy before they finally kill us which is a very high high ratio and he said that means
And I call it the John Wayne theory.
The John Wayne theory is you fight to the end and you die a hero.
He turned and he said, you know, that idea is totally stupid.
He said, why do you do it that way?
All you want to do is you shoot one today and you run.
And you shoot one tomorrow and you run.
And in one year, you have just killed 365 people.
and I'm still alive, what is the ratio then?
365 to one compared to your 10 to one.
So they had a different idea about what is war.
War to us was fight to the John Wayne, the Alamo, fight to the end.
where they had an idea that you hit and you run.
If you get into a situation where you think you're going to be surrounded, get out.
But you're still allowed to fight another day, where we will sit there and keep fighting.
So it's different ideas.
I think their type of fighting could not, we could not work together.
If that's what you mean by the arm, they could not fight with us because we had different theories.
Guerrilla fighting or in the jungle fighting, perfect.
But we did not fight that way, and that was the difference.
Did you ever actually conduct a small unit action or any action?
Oh, yeah, yeah, yeah.
As I showed you earlier, going into Khe Sanh was the biggest joke.
We thought we knew we died at Khe Sanh.
It was a... And we walked right into it.
A story out of Khe Sanh.
1-9, there was nothing left of 1-9 or 2.
2-9 was just chopped up.

There were areas they talked about, and I never saw this area, but they were talking about at night when you set up your concertina wire, you put cans of rocks in it, or you put a piece of metal into the concertina wire to where someone touches a rattle.
You make noises, and you tell what the enemy is there touching the wire.
Some of those nights, it got so dark.
You couldn't see, and you kept asking for flares, but after a while, the enemy then sees you, so you can't put too many flares out.
They said one of the sides during this time period, at night it got so dark they couldn't see.

The next morning when the sun came up, they noticed that all the hands were taken off and little white crosses were placed in that position, saying that the enemy got into the concertina wire, made no noise, showed that they could have crossed into the wire any time they wanted to.
Personally, I was too scared to believe something like that.
I'm saying, God, if they could do that, then why are we still here?
I mean, they were really pounding the hell out of us.
It felt like you couldn't sleep at night.
You tried the best.
You would sleep for maybe, it felt like 30 seconds because a shell was coming in almost that often.
It was just constant pounding.
But I guess we're, as Marines, we're just too stupid to give up.
But one of the guys in a unit got his flight back.
It's the day that you have to report to the name, you're going home.
And he's in the middle of, right in the middle of Khe Sanh, surrounded by, we thought, the entire Asian population was around us, because hell, we were totally surrounded.
We started laughing at him, that you ain't going home, mother, you're going to die right here.
We laughed at him for about a day.
It must have been the second day this idiot stood up, took his helmet off,
We have what they call little Volkswagens.
We call them a mule.
They're like little Volkswagens.
They took all the parts of them and made a flat bed across them.
You had one place to steer it and carry things on it.
He stood up on a mule and he just hollered out to the wire, people, I quit.
I'm putting my rifle down.
I'm putting my helmet down.
I am not fighting anymore.
I am going home.
Okay?
He gets in the mule.
And he takes off, he puts some mail on the back behind this mule.
He takes off to Dong Ha, which is right next to Quang Tri, going home.
When he left, he snuck out.
He just didn't just, you know, everybody watched him and waved at him, but he snuck out.
We knew when he got out, you know, we'd never see that mother again.
He's going to be just dead meat somewhere.
About four hours later, he calls from Quang Tri.
Nobody stopped him.
He just saw no one the entire distance.
Again, the Vietnamese believe that people that are crazy are sacred.
Anybody crazy enough to go through three divisions of North Vietnamese regulars
Got to be crazy.
And he made it all the way back.
You know, nuts like, things like that always happen.
You know, you wonder.
You know, everybody then started saying, people, I give up.
You know, but it didn't work after they kept pounding the hell out of it.
All right.
What was the typical action you would describe that you were involved in as a, in those later periods as a patrol?
Okay.
I classify Vietnam as two wars.
You have a good war and then you have a bad war.
About, I would say, 66 through 69, it was a good war.
Maybe even kind of 70, if you want to.
It was to where the American public was not that much against it.
People over there were still fighting the war.
I was there during that time period.
The bad war is the time period where
People coming over were the protesters, the people that did not, of course, nobody wanted to be there, but these were the ones that were picketing and fighting against the war.
So their patrols, I heard about, you know, smoking grass, going on patrol, most of the guys would die.
I would be really afraid to have been over there during the 70s because of how...
Sloppy, real sloppy, these people were.
I always heard, you know, these guys that talk afterwards about being heroes.
You know, there's no hero in Vietnam.
All it was is a bunch of guys that try to stay alive.
Some of them did some of the weirdest things by being heroes.
But anyway, the Enormous Patrol for us was very easygoing.
We worked together very well.

the four guys that I was with some of my I call every so often but I've not seen him since we left since I've left Vietnam or they left also of course I didn't ask you I didn't answer your question too well other typical action what was it like you mean going on patrol yeah most of the times we had a three-day patrol four-day patrol you're really going for us a lot of times we were just out

seeing what's out there and if you're talking about different types we had a patrol you'd go out past the wire for a few days just checking to see what's or even one day you're going out just see what's out there and coming back you had other ones where we would have to go to vanden grift or to any place like that where you just take off and put it all the way there gosh i wish i could in the jungle was uh
The most frightening of them all to me.
The jungle was scary because you couldn't see ahead of them.
It was so hot.
There's no sun.
The humidity just drained the energy out of you.
The heat was just terrible.
But you couldn't see.
That was a big thing.
You were walking along.
You had to be so quiet because you make any noise, those people can almost walk 20 feet away from you, and you will never even see them.
You'll only hear or smell them.
Same way for our direction.
Typical action.
Let's see if I can give one.
We took three days, or two days of C-rations, or three days, we were out for three days.
We used C-rations or K-rations, which tasted like, you know, 20-year-old vomit.
And we couldn't heat it up.
We had to eat it cold, which made it even taste worse.
But you were so hot and so drained of fluid, you really didn't want to eat anything.
All you wanted to do was take down the liquids.
God, I...
I wish I could help you more on it, but that's just when we'd go out on patrols.
We were scared.
Of course, there are fun times.
I mean, there's a weird time, too.
Now, that's what I like to remember, the weird times.
You'll get out, and you'll have these monkeys.
We call them rock apes.
They'll throw rocks at you.
You're sitting down there on the ground, not bothering anybody.
Also, you have these things thrown at you from, we call them rock apes.
They'll throw anything they can get their hands on.
to get you out of their area.
They thought that was their area.
And idiots like us, instead of shooting them, we throw rocks back at them.
And then you have a firefight between monkeys and marines over their little area.
There was a time where we went after a bingo tiger.
I showed you the picture, didn't I?
I didn't shoot it.
Some guy shot a... We went out on patrol to kill a bingo tiger.
There was like an operation of maybe...
Four or five hundred went out on a hunt of this rabid bingo tiger.
It was told whoever got it could keep it.
It was their skin.
They could take the skin home.
A Marine shot it with an M16, one shot by total accident.
The guy said he was just shooting in the area and the tiger ran into the bullet.
But he hit him right in the head, just blew the top of his head off.
Well, they drug it back, they hooked it up in the camp, they hooked it on a telephone pole, and let's sit there like an honor, like this is what we got.
Found out the next day it's rabbits.
So the colonel of our company found out that we have to burn it.
What you have to do to a rabbit animal out there is you dig a hole, you bury it,
You dig a hole first, then you cover it with gasoline, you burn it, pour lye on it, then you bury it, and you don't get away from that area for a while.
That's what they did.
But our colonel didn't.
101 Airborne just moved up right next to us.
We never saw stakes.
We never had T-bone stakes.
They did.

Their colonel said, God, I wish I had that skin because, man, that's a beautiful thing to take home, to lay on the ground, to say that, you know, he'd probably go home and say he shot it himself, you know.
Who in the hell would know?
So our colonel, knowing it's rabbit, said, I'll tell you what, the guy, the boy doesn't want the skin at all, or the animal.
He gave it to me.
I'll tell you what, if you give me one of your bins full of steaks to feed my guys, we'll give you the skin.
The guy said, hey, great, we'll do that.
So he takes the steaks that he was going to give to his own servicemen, the Army, which hell, they get them all the time, gave them to us.
He has, we call them like ditzy dumpsters, or big metal containers of refrigeration.
Well, he only had one refrigerator left with the steaks that the guys were going to eat for the rest of the month, which is mostly ground meat and stuff like this.
So he throws that carcass into that, their other refrigerator, waiting until someone processes the skin, okay?
So he called over his doctors.
We already had this big, ditzy dumpster with steaks.
We had a fantastic barbecue.
We just, we ate and ate, because we had email, because we knew that as soon as he found out that that thing is rabid, that we, okay, to the Army.
Great steaks.

He had to, the funny part, this is what I heard, I don't know if it was true or not, but I heard that the colonel was so embarrassed, their colonel, was so embarrassed that he was being snookered by a Marine colonel
that he couldn't tell everybody that the thing was rabid.
He just snuck out and burned it.
But he put it in with this meat, which contaminated the meat.
He was so embarrassed by it, he didn't want to tell anybody he did do that.
So he let the guys eat the meat, you know, that was then contaminated.
But who knows?
They could have done that.
That's normal.
How would you analyze the progress of the war while you were there?
There was no progress.
When I got there,
All I saw when I got there, the progress to me was the building up of Quang Tri.
When I entered Vietnam, I was stationed with the 3rd Marine Division, and they just moved up.
They were first, I think, in Dong Ha.
I wasn't there yet.
Dong Ha is a little farther north than Quang Tri.
And they were from the other side of the DMZ.
They could rocket to Dong Ha.
So it's
It was a little too close to the north, so I think they wanted to build a base a little farther south where rockets won't hit it.
Dong Ha base was still there, but they moved down to Quang Tri.
When I got there, they were just starting to build Quang Tri up.
We went from tents to  now, this army wasn't there yet, so we were stealing plywood and things from the Seabees or whatever we need stuff from.
So we built  within the first year, we had wooden tents
you know, the size of me out of wood, things like this that we got from the Seabees or whatever we could steal from other people.
But that's the money field.
I saw no advancement except you go out on patrol one day, you hit a village the next day, you go back, the village is, you know, taken over again.
We didn't gain anything.
I never thought we ever gained land.
I never saw it gain.
I just saw us lose.
Or you go into a village, you know they're scared.
You know that you can tell that they're scared.
They...
They tell you there's no one there, and you know there is, but you know that when you leave that village, they're going to move back in.
And we lived in that village.
They'd help us if we lived in the village, but then we would be gone, and we didn't see Viet Cong at all.
We fought straight North Vietnamese rebels.
We knew they were going to come back and live in that village, so they were more afraid of them than they were of us.

do you feel the policies guiding the world the war were too vague or inconsistent with actually what was going on oh yeah uh that made it difficult to uh the policy we i didn't know if we had a policy in vietnam except go over and just a lot of times i blame west marlin i blame uh i don't know if i'd blame johnson because i don't think johnson i think it was allowed to that's how i really feel i feel that the army
and not the Army lied to him, I think that the CIA came up with a lot of situations that did not, were not true.
When Westmoreland came up and said, we need 50,000 men and we can do this, and so he gives them 50,000 men and says, we're a little wrong, we need another 50,000.
The escalation of war, a lot of people blame Johnson for the escalation.
I don't, I just think that he was going along with what he was trusting,
his advisors, and I think his advisors were all wrong with what they were doing in the policy.
You don't believe me?
He was part of the naval pump.
Your teacher was part of the...
Right.
He served as a gunner out on the ship.
Okay.
My one time with the Navy, I've got to tell you this one.
When you call in fire support,
We call in fire support by calling our rear or having a frequency to go to.
And our frequency is mostly a 105 howitzer or a 155 howitzer.
And that's what mostly we got sometimes.
And when you call it in, they check your coordinates to make sure they're not in a friendly area.
Then they'll ask for smoke.
And they'll send one round.
And sometimes you're hit so hard, you say, forget the smoke.
Just come in with it, because we're really being hit.
And sometimes they do.
But sometimes it's like a grab bag.
You're knowing you're going to get 105s or 155s, but you don't know what else you're going to get.
We were out.
And this was about 6.30 in the evening, just starting dust.
We can see them moving around.
We were near a rice pad.
what they call scrub brush.
There's a lot of this stuff around.
We can see there must have been about 30 or 40 of them out there.
At least for us it felt like 5,000, but there's only a few.
They looked like they were trying to surround us, but we wanted to hit them, so we called in for support.
What we were hoping for was a jet or a helicopter to come in because
They're easier to work with because they're right there on top of you.
But you get mostly 105s and 155s.
So we called in, and the guy on the radio was calling in our coordinates.
And he said he kept hollering at this guy.
And we said, what do you got?
He says, I can't tell where this guy is, but he sounds like he is 5,000 miles away.
He's talking so far away from his mic.
May I have this?
He was talking so far away from the mic.
We couldn't understand what he meant by that.
This guy said, just give me your coordinates.
We gave him the coordinates, and he said, I'm going to drop smoke.
I will wait, and then tell me if you want to fire for effect.
That must have been, oh, a few minutes later.
We looked up, and in my mind I said, where's the train?
Because it sounded like a locomotive coming over.
And all of a sudden, the whole ground just shook.
And he said, fire!
And the guy on the bus just thought he meant fire for effect.
And he put three shells.
It was New Jersey.
He put three shells.
All we were doing was ruining it.
We thought the world came to an end.
I did not know shells get that big.
We got about, oh, we must have ran, it felt like for days, but I mean, we ran for a couple hundred yards, laid back, and we said, God, we don't want that anymore.
They should have said, we're the New Jersey.
Please be a bit advised.
You're going to get a train coming over your head, and we're going to blow up an entire grid coordinate for you.
That was the only time, and I think after that we got real gunshot, but I never called anything in because we were afraid we'd get to New Jersey again.
God, I mean, that is the most powerful shot we have ever, I've ever had.
He was on me in New Jersey.
Thank you for letting me shit in my pants.
All right.
Did you see any atrocities or war crimes?
No.
No, I didn't see any.
Wait a minute, wait a minute.
Let's take this back a minute.
Wait a minute.
If you mean by atrocities, no, I saw no atrocities.
I heard of some.
For instance, that's what I was going to try to get to.
I don't know if that's considered the same.
I heard of a guy going down in a...
Picking up the enemy, having three of them in the back of a... We never had these beautiful trucks.
We always had dump trucks or a deuce and a half.
We never had the beautiful cars or the beautiful trucks with the covers on the back and the beautiful seats.
The Army had that.
We had nothing.
When you pick up three guys or three of the enemy that you've caught, you don't want them to talk.
I've heard of them guys that would take them and tie their hands together, throw them off the back of the truck.
And just drag them.
And then when you have nothing left of the guys with these arms, then you say, next.
And they say, by that time, the guys are talking.
You know, find out where the enemy is.
I don't know if that's true.
I never saw it.
I've always heard about stuff like that.
And you say, yay for the good guys.
You let them drag them a while.
But that's it.
Do you feel your involvement in the war was the right thing to do?
Wow.
Hindsight is great sight.
At the time, I thought I was fighting for God, mom, and apple pie.
That, I really believe.
I still believe today, I've got to, or I would... Everything that I did was actually worthless if I don't believe that I fought for the United States and for what I really believed in.
But it gets tougher to look at it that way.
I believe the war was...
was wrong.
At the time, what we wanted to do was turn the whole country into glass, just nuke it and make it into another Disney world for the future generations.
But I personally today look back and say I don't think we should have been there.
But at the time, I have to believe that I was there for a cause.
Because at that time, it was a good war.
It wasn't a bad war yet.
So we still believe it was a good war.
That's your question?
Oh, yeah.
Let's see.

So we've been reading materials that bring to light the fact that South Vietnam was so permeated with corruption and civil dissent that the VC or the National Liberation Front were in such firm control that there was basically nothing that could have been done.
Do you believe this is true, that no amount of aid, men, troops,
unified national action from the union or anything could have prevented?
THE PRESIDENT.
No, Vietnam was, the country was wrong.
I don't know if it was our foreign policy, which I think it was.
It wasn't the military fault, since you're an ADM, I can't have to say it that way.
It really was not the military, because they fought with the politicians and made them fight.
And that's sad.
That type of war should never happen again.
And it's not the war, it's that letting politicians fight a war.
And I think that's what happened.
We went into a country that the politicians absolutely corrupted.
We destroyed their economy.
We destroyed their self-image.
We destroyed everything that one country could destroy on another country.
And we did it for the sake of democracy.
And that was not the military that did it mostly.
It was the politicians at the time, and our own politicians, trying to make a buck.
Some of us, not politicians, but some of our company owners of big industries was making a lot of money off this war.
They'll do any calls.
But there was no hope for Vietnam.
Vietnam never, ever had a chance.
What was your homecoming like?
Bad.
By the time I got home, oh, wait, let me tell you about home.
I entered, when I left Vietnam, I entered Da Nang.
When we go home, we get flight dates.

How did you change during your time in Vietnam?
I grew up.
I was a little kid.
